{
  "text": "Let (k, \u2202) denote a differential field of characteristic zero whose constant field C is assumed to be algebraically closed. The usual case is k = C(x) with \u2202 = d dx . We consider a linear differential system [A] : Y \u2032 = AY with A \u2208 Mat(n, k). We refer to the book [CITATION_1] for the differential Galois theory used here. Let K denote a Picard-Vessiot extension for [A] . Let G := Aut \u2202 (K/k) be the differential Galois group of [A] and g = Lie(G) its Lie algebra. We also write Lie([A]) for the Lie algebra of the Galois group G of Y \u2032 = AY . The C-vector space of solutions of [A] in K n is noted V . Remark that the selection of a fundamental solution matrix U \u2208 GL n (K) of [A] is equivalent with the choice of a basis (Y j ) j=1...n of V . The differential module associated to [A] is noted M = (k n , \u2207 A ). The connexion \u2207 A admits A as its matrix in the canonical basis (e j ) j=1...n of k n and is defined by",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "118081938"
  },
  "bib_entries": {
    "118081938": {
      "title": "Galois theory of linear differential equations",
      "abstract": "Linear differential equations form the central topic of this volume, Galois theory being the unifying theme. ::: A large number of aspects are presented: algebraic theory especially differential Galois theory, formal theory, classification, algorithms to decide solvability in finite terms, monodromy and Hilbert's 21st problem, asymptotics and summability, the inverse problem and linear differential equations in positive characteristic. The appendices aim to help the reader with concepts used, from algebraic geometry, linear algebraic groups, sheaves, and tannakian categories that are used. ::: This volume will become a standard reference for all mathematicians in this area of mathematics, including graduate students."
    }
  }
}